4. Round 1 — The Task
Core Objective: Build a complete, real-world OpenEnv environment that an AI agent can learn from through the standard step() / reset() / state() API.

Critical constraint: The environment must simulate a real-world task — not games, not toys. The hackathon explicitly calls out examples like email triage, code review, data cleaning, scheduling, customer support, and content moderation.

When Round 1 opens fully, you’ll choose 1 of 4–5 problem statements and build an OpenEnv environment around it.

Functional Requirements
OpenEnv Spec Compliance: You must implement the full OpenEnv interface with typed Pydantic models for Observation, Action, and Reward. The three core APIs — step(action), reset(), and state() — must all work correctly. You also need an openenv.yaml metadata file, and the environment must pass openenv validate.

Minimum 3 Tasks with Graders: Each task defines a concrete objective an agent must accomplish. Tasks should scale in difficulty (easy, medium, hard), and each needs a programmatic grader that scores performance on a 0.0–1.0 scale with clear, deterministic success/failure criteria.

Meaningful Reward Function: Rewards must provide signal over the full trajectory (not just binary end-of-episode). They should reward partial progress and penalize undesirable behavior like infinite loops or destructive actions.

Baseline Inference Script: Must use the OpenAI API client, read credentials from environment variables (OPENAI_API_KEY), and produce reproducible baseline scores on all 3 tasks.

Non-Functional Requirements
Deployment: Must deploy to a Hugging Face Space tagged with openenv, with a working Dockerfile that builds and runs cleanly.

Documentation: README must include environment description/motivation, action/observation space definitions, task descriptions with expected difficulty, setup/usage instructions, and baseline scores.

Additional Endpoints to Expose:
/baseline — triggers inference and returns scores for all 3 tasks
/grader — returns grader score after an episode
/tasks — returns list of tasks and action schema

Scoring Breakdown (100 points total)
Real-world utility — 30% (the single biggest weight): Does it model a genuine task? Would someone use this to train/evaluate agents? Scoring ranges from 0–5 for toy problems up to 26–30 for something that fills a real gap in the RL/agent community.
Task & grader quality — 25%: Are tasks well-defined? Do graders produce 0.0–1.0 scores deterministically? Is there meaningful difficulty progression? Does the hard task genuinely challenge frontier models?

Environment design — 20%: Clean state management via reset(), well-designed action/observation types, useful reward signals (not sparse), and sensible episode boundaries.

Code quality & spec compliance — 15%: openenv validate passes, Docker builds and runs, HF Space deploys, baseline script reproduces scores.

Creativity & novelty — 10%: Novel problem domain, interesting reward mechanics, clever design, original approach.

6. Evaluation Pipeline
The evaluation happens in three phases:

Phase 1 — Automated Validation (Pass/Fail Gate): HF Space deploys, OpenEnv spec compliance, Dockerfile builds, baseline reproduces, 3+ tasks with graders. If you fail this, you’re out immediately.

Phase 2 — Agentic Evaluation (Scored): Your baseline agent is re-run, a standard Open LLM agent (e.g., Nemotron 3 Super) is run against all environments, and score variance is checked.

Phase 3 — Human Review: Top submissions are reviewed by Meta and Hugging Face engineers for real-world utility, creativity, and exploit checks.

Disqualification Criteria
Environment does not deploy or respond; plagiarized or trivially modified existing environments; graders that always return the same score; no baseline inference script.

The OpenEnv Framework — Technical Deep Dive
OpenEnv is a client-server architecture where environments run inside Docker containers and communicate via WebSocket. The framework has clear separation between client-side (what agents use) and server-side (where the environment logic lives).
Architecture: Clients (EnvClient subclasses) connect via WebSocket to Docker containers running FastAPI servers that host the actual Environment logic. Both async and sync APIs are supported.

Project Structure (from openenv init): The scaffold creates models.py for Pydantic dataclasses, client.py for the EnvClient, a server directory with the environment implementation and FastAPI app, Dockerfile, openenv.yaml, and pyproject.toml.

Building an environment involves 5 steps: Define your models (Action, Observation, State), implement environment APIs (step/reset/state), create the FastAPI server, build a Docker image, and subclass the HTTP client with parsing methods.

